  "prompt": "How is Earth's axis tilt measured?",
  "response": "Earth's axis tilt, also known as **obliquity**, is measured as the angle between Earth's rotational axis and its orbital plane (the **ecliptic plane**). It is determined using astronomical observations and precise calculations. Here's how it is measured:\n\n1. **Reference Plane**: The ecliptic plane is the plane of Earth's orbit around the Sun. The tilt is measured relative to this plane.\n\n2. **Pole Orientation**: Earth's rotational axis points toward the celestial poles (North and South Celestial Poles). The angle between this axis and the ecliptic plane is the axis tilt.\n\n3. **Astronomical Observations**:\n   - The tilt can be observed by measuring the **elevation of the celestial poles** above the horizon at different latitudes.\n   - It is also inferred from the **variation in the Sun's declination** (its position north or south of the celestial equator) throughout the year.\n\n4. **Mathematical Calculation**:\n   - The tilt is calculated using the difference in the Sun's declination between solstices. For example, during the June solstice, the Sun's declination is approximately +23.5\u00b0, and during the December solstice, it is -23.5\u00b0.\n   - The tilt is half the difference between these extremes.\n\n5. **Modern Techniques**:\n   - Satellite data and precise measurements of Earth's orientation are used to determine the tilt accurately.\n   - The **International Terrestrial Reference Frame (ITRF)** and other geodetic systems provide data on Earth's orientation in space.\n\nAs of 2023, Earth's axial tilt is approximately **23.4 degrees**, though it varies slightly over long periods (between 22.1\u00b0 and 24.5\u00b0) due to gravitational interactions with other celestial bodies. This variation is part of a cycle known as the **Milankovitch cycles**.",
